</PRE><HR><PRE>
    Hm, wild guess: ANY archimedean polyhedra should do. 

Regular tetrahedra do not, unless you allow cusps (vertices at infinity).
The tetrahedron has too small a solid angle to fill the hyperbolic space
around a point (with a symmetric vertex neighborhood).

I haven't thought about the others in detail, but
I'm also not convinced about snub cubes and snub dodecahedra.
Maybe the rest are ok.
You'd have to be careful how you glue them together
(e.g. for the buckyball you have to give the hexagon faces a 1/6 twist
before gluing so that you don't get two pentagons on the same edge).

By the way, there was a minor detail wrong in my post --
buckyballs don't have one dihedral, they have two, one (x) between
pairs of hexagons and one (y) between hexagons and pentagons.
The volume one wants is the one for which x+2y=360.
